      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nWhen we began our studies on multiplication tables, we observed that it is possible—with the help of squared paper—to represent the tables graphically, creating shapes such as lines and triangles",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b6428e19-afcf-4d3b-916d-46e5a332ef53",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "In this text, we will deepen our understanding of triangles and explore their relationship with two other multiplication tables.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_triangle",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Triangle\n\nBefore proceeding, to further clarify the concepts introduced earlier and what we will explore next, we have filled the lower triangle formed by the connected points of the multiplication table of one",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b6428e19-afcf-4d3b-916d-46e5a332ef53",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htChart\"><canvas aria-label=\"chart\" id=\"chart1\" style=\"width:30em !important; height:20em !important;\"></canvas></p><p class=\"desc\">Chart 1: Points of the multiplication table connected, forming a straight line <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('b77ec8fc-c988-45f3-82f8-03b136bf1aa9'); return false;\">Chart JS</a>.</div></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: Defining the Triangle</b><br /><br />Looking at Chart 1, where the triangular area is highlighted, how would you describe this shape?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Compare your definition with a simplified version of the one provided by Eric W. Weisstein",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "f33dbf7c-924c-453f-bee5-a19388e75109",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W., Triangle",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<ul class=\"citation\"><li><i>\"A triangle is a closed shape with three sides and three angles (formed by the intersection of its sides)...\"</i></li> </ul>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Beyond this general definition, Weisstein notes that the right triangle shown in the chart has specific components with distinct names. In Chart 2, we identify these elements and label them",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "f33dbf7c-924c-453f-bee5-a19388e75109",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W., Triangle",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "56edda64-d96e-4106-b1f8-676a235b818c",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W., Right Triangle",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"imgcenterresponsive\"><svg height=\"245\" width=\"450\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\"><path d=\"M425 5 L75 200 L425 200 Z\" style=\"fill:none;stroke:green;stroke-width:3\" /><rect x=\"404\" y=\"179\" width=\"20\" height=\"20\" stroke=\"green\" fill=\"none\" stroke-width=\"3\" /><text x=\"125\" y=\"192\" font-size=\"1.5em\">α</text><text x=\"401\" y=\"45\" font-size=\"1.5em\">β</text><text x=\"235\" y=\"95\" font-size=\"2.5em\">c</text><text x=\"428\" y=\"120\" font-size=\"2.5em\">b</text><text x=\"265\" y=\"230\" font-size=\"2.5em\">a</text></svg></p><p class=\"desc\">Chart 2: Right triangle with its components labeled.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "- **a**, **b** and **c**: The sides of the triangle. Sides **a** and **b** are called **legs**, while **c** is the **hypotenuse**.\n- **α**, **β**, and <i class=\"fa-regular fa-square\"></i>: The angles formed by the intersection of the sides. The square symbol ( <i class=\"fa-regular fa-square\"></i> ) marking the angle between the horizontal and vertical sides is called the **right angle**.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_general_formula",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### A General Formula\n\nIn the multiplication table, we multiply different numbers **N** by a fixed value, obtaining their products. In the first text, we performed these operations and concluded that the following formulas exist for the multiplication tables of zero and one",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b6428e19-afcf-4d3b-916d-46e5a332ef53",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math><mi>0</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>0</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>N</mi> </math></center></p><p><center><math><mi>N</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>1</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>N</mi> </math></center></p><p class=\"desc\">Forrmula 1: Formulas used in the multiplication tables of zero and one.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "These two formulas can be expressed more generally",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "79d126c9-39ac-4679-904b-4ab69558e44e",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math><mi>r</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>a</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>N</mi> </math></center></p><p class=\"desc\">Formula 2: General formula for multiplication tables.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "In this formula:\n- *r*: is the product of the multiplication.\n *N*: is the factor representing the counted number.\n- *a*: in addition to being a multiplication factor, it receives different names in various contexts. However, regardless of its name, its function in multiplication remains the same: to modify a point's position relative to the horizontal line. For this reason, one of its names is **slope coefficient** (or **angular coefficient**).",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: The Factor *a*</b><br /><br />When **a = 0**, the results become points aligned along the horizontal axis.<br />Cuando a = 1, the results form points along the diagonal, dividing the grid paper into two equal triangles.<br /><br />What would you expect to happen when <b>a</b> takes the values 2 and 3</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_two",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Multiply by Two (2)\n\nWhen we began studying this section, First Steps, the first subject related to the human body that we examined was symmetry—the existence of two sides that mirror each other",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "20b14681-88c0-438a-a273-a0902ae5db38",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team, Our Sides Are Equal",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2023",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table class=\"book_navigation\"><tr><td>Left hand</td><td>Right hand</td></tr><tr><td><img id=\"imgLH\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgLH', '0%')\" src=\"images/Left_Hand.png\" class=\"imgcenter\"/></td><td><img id=\"imgRH\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgRH', '0%')\" src=\"images/Right_Hand.png\" class=\"imgcenter\"/></td></tr></table></p><p class=\"desc\">Figure 1: Hands reprsentation. The source codes are available in project GitHub (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('240800f3-ede4-4deb-9d4e-915a3a03fa68'); return false;\">History Tracers Team, <span class=\"htdate\"></span>, Source code</a>).</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "The figure shows a person's two hands raised with all fingers extended.",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Dr. Francisco Barriga Puente, in his studies on the Brazilian Indigenous numerical system, identified a binary system based on the numbers one (1) and two (2). To represent larger values, such as six (6), they used repeated sums",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ceffba8a-43be-4de3-a5c8-27cdf81311b1",
                     "text": "Puente, Francisco Barriga",
                     "page": "pp. 33",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2020",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math><mi>2</mi> <mo>and</mo> <mi>2</mi> <mo>and</mo> <mi>2</mi> </math></center></p><p class=\"desc\">Representation of the number six in a binary Indigenous system.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "These examples help us construct the table of two.\n\n#### Building the Table\n\nTo create the table of two (2), we apply Formula 2, assigning the factor **a** the value two (2), which gives the following results:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div id=\"mParent2\" style=\"margin: auto; text-align: center;\"></div></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Graphical Representation\n\nThis time, instead of drawing points and connecting them in separate charts (as in previous methods), we will use the same chart, following the steps outlined earlier",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b6428e19-afcf-4d3b-916d-46e5a332ef53",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htChart\"><canvas aria-label=\"chart\" id=\"chart2\" style=\"width:30em !important; height:20em !important;\"></canvas></p><p class=\"desc\">Chart 3: Points from the table of two connected, forming a straight line. Chart created using <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('b77ec8fc-c988-45f3-82f8-03b136bf1aa9'); return false;\">Chart JS</a>.</div></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "When comparing **Chart 3** with **Chart 1**, the figures appear nearly identical. However, the differences become evident when we plot the tables of one and two together in a single chart:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htChart\"><canvas aria-label=\"chart\" id=\"chart3\" style=\"width:30em !important; height:20em !important;\"></canvas></p><p class=\"desc\">Chart 4: Points from the tables of one and two connected, forming two lines. Chart built using <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('b77ec8fc-c988-45f3-82f8-03b136bf1aa9'); return false;\">Chart JS</a>.</div></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "In **Chart 4**, we observe that—in addition to dividing the squared paper—the values on the vertical axis are greater for the products multiplied by two. Furthermore, the distance from the horizontal axis increases, resulting in a steeper angle.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_three",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Multiplying by Three (3)\n\nIn addition to the right triangle, in this and subsequent texts, we will also use the isosceles triangle, which has at least two equal sides. As a consequence, if we draw a straight line from the vertex (where the equal sides meet) to the base (opposite side), we obtain two symmetrical sides, as shown in **Chart 5**",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "61e568be-8a3a-4f53-bd2d-e9ce113cf68b",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"imgcenterresponsive\"><svg width=\"450\" height=\"300\"><polygon points=\"265,10 125,280 405,280\" style=\"fill:none;stroke:lightgreen;stroke-width:3\" /><text x=\"140\" y=\"270\" font-size=\"1.5em\">α</text><text x=\"370\" y=\"270\" font-size=\"1.5em\">α</text><g fill=\"none\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"1\"><path stroke-dasharray=\"5,5\" d=\"M265 14 l0 270\" /></g></svg></p><p class=\"desc\">Chart 5: Isosceles triangle with equal angles and sides.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "The number three also appears in various objects and structures, such as the Type E Complex in Caracol, Belize. Within it, we observe three structures responsible for marking the seasons of the year",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "e7c7458b-0c63-4485-9c7b-4640edcd9122",
                     "text": "Inomata, T.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2017",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><iframe src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/UBMUR-3hHz0?si=mn22_mrWLJ23ueeO\" title=\"YouTube video player\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen style=\"aspect-ratio: 16 / 9; width: 55% !important;\"></iframe><br />Video 1: Type E Complex in Caracol, Belize. Recorded during a site visit on <htdate0>.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2015",
                     "month": "4",
                     "day": "26"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Building the Table\n\nTo construct the multiplication table for three (3), we again apply **Formula 2**, assigning the value three (3) to the factor **a**, yielding the following results:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div id=\"mParent3\" style=\"margin: auto; text-align: center;\"></div></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Drawing the Table\n\n**Chart 6** displays the values from the table of 3:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htChart\"><canvas aria-label=\"chart\" id=\"chart4\" style=\"width:30em !important; height:20em !important;\"></canvas></p><p class=\"desc\">Chart 6: Points from the table of three connected to form a straight line. Chart created using the <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('b77ec8fc-c988-45f3-82f8-03b136bf1aa9'); return false;\">Chart JS</a>.</div></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 3: Relationship Between Numbers</b><br /><br />The table of one (1) produced points distant from the horizontal line. Using the table of two (2) placed them even farther away.<br /><br />Does the table of three (3) bring the points closer to or farther from the horizontal line?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "To visualize this better, let’s plot all three tables together:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htChart\"><canvas aria-label=\"chart\" id=\"chart5\" style=\"width:30em !important; height:20em !important;\"></canvas></p><p class=\"desc\">Chart 7: Points from the tables of one, two, and three connected, forming three straight lines. Chart built with <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('b77ec8fc-c988-45f3-82f8-03b136bf1aa9'); return false;\">Chart JS</a>.</div></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "**Chart 7** shows the three tables with their respective points plotted and connected. From this, we conclude:\n- As we increase factor **a** (the angular coeficient), the distance from the horizontal line (and the angle) also increases\n- The value six (6) appears in the table of two (2) when **N = 3**, while the same value (6) appears in the table of (3) when **N = 2**. This illustrates that the order of factors does not change the product.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
